bug.short_desc: Eclipse does not pass all annotated classes to annotation processor

long_desc.thetext: Is there some advice on how to debug what is going on here? I'm all for doing leg work to help solved what is going on, but with the magic compilation of modules I'm at a lost where I should be looking for debugging. I currently have some devs switching to intellij just because it gives consistent results so we are really ready to get this resolved.

Hi, Bin. Sorry not to respond sooner.
I've heard reports of this in the past, and I certainly believe it to be real, but I've never been able to reproduce it reliably; e.g., there's a test in the suite that generates a project with thousands of files and then compiles it, and I've never gotten it to fail :-( So it is hard to pursue.
It has been a few years since I looked into it but as I recall there is a constant in the JDT builder code (in jdt.core plugin) that determines how many files can be compiled at once; when there are more files than that in a project, compilation is chunked. I have always suspected that this might have something to do with it. You might want to experiment with changing that constant and then recompiling the jdt.core plugin?
Reassigning this bug to JDT/Core component just in case any of the core folks have any insight. Feel free to reassign back to APT with or without comment.

Also, there doesn't seem to be a problem with compilation from the Compiler.compile(ICompilationUnit[] sourceUnits) method. Every annotated module that is passed to that method is properly passed to our AP. I suppose the bigger question that would aid in my debugging is how are all the other classes compiled if not through the Compiler.compile() method?

I sill haven't found the constant you spoke of, but I got to thinking maybe I could rearrange the src folders order so that all the annotated modules might fit in the same compile round. That has led to some success as I had all the classes passed to the AP. This worked about 10 times until it failed after a restart and rebuild. The classes that failed to be include were near the bottom, so I figured after the restart was some how including more classes than before. So I created a linked src folder near the top and included just the packages with the failed classes. This again seems to be working.
Now this still just a workaround since adding a class or 2 higher in the src folder order, might push one of the annotated module classes out and into another compile round.

I guess we are talking about:
org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.builder.AbstractImageBuilder.MAX_AT_ONCE
This constant is set to 2000. Given your number of 4412 source files, changing the constant might have an effect, i.e., help us understand the root cause of your problem.

Bin, did you get a chance to experiment with the MAX_AT_ONCE ? Please let us know your findings.
Thanks for the reminder, but I have not played with that as of yet but I hoe to work on it this weekend though.

Finally got to this and here's what I see. Using 4.3M2 on OSX, if I leave the MAX_AT_ONCE value at 2000, then my AnnotationProcessor will be called in 2 rounds with 18 annotated classes in the 1st round and 2 in the 2nd round. Now if I raise the limit to 5000, then the AP will be called with 23 classes in 1 round. I then rearranged the classpath to push the jmx-support/src folder further down in the list to the 2nd processing round. While this worked, but we are still missing classes in the middle. Here's where things take on a WTH feel because I consistently miss the same 3 annotated classes. My classpath is currently laid out like the following:
<classpathentry kind="src" path="lisa-cloud/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="acl/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="reporting/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="virtualize/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="ws-xml/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="httpweb/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="j2ee/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="esb/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/lisa-editor/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/com.itko.lisa.tests.api/src/main/java"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/patches/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/utils/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/beanshell-editor/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="netbeans/xmldiff-viewer/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="lisaint/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="itko-util/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="lisa-remote/JavaAgent/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="lisa-web/web20bridge/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="jdbridge/jdbrige/src"/> <classpathentry excluding="jms/Sonic7.0/src/" kind="src" path="lisa/regressions"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="itko-util/tests/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="lisa-remote/tests/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="virtualize/tests/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="jmx-support/src"/> <classpathentry kind="src" path="lisa/src"/> [310 jar file entries here] <classpathentry kind="src" path="pf-core-bridge/src"/>
Most of the source folders have 1 or more annotated module classes, specifically there are 3 annotated classes under the lisa/src folder and 1 under the jmx-support/src, lisa-web/web20bridge/src and pf-core-bridge/src folders. When the MAX_AT_ONCE value is left at the default 2000, then I get 17 from the other src folders in the 1st round and then the 3 annotated classes from the jmx-support/src, lisa-web/web20bridge/src and pf-core-bridge/src folders in the 2nd round. However I never get the 3 classes from under lisa/src. That only happens if I raise the value to 5000 (the only value I've tried BTW).
So how do I go about debugging why we keep consistently missing the final 3 classes?
Walter, do you have any idea what might be going on here? I am moving to APT for your investigation, for I don't have a clue what's wrong.

(In reply to comment #12) > Walter, do you have any idea what might be going on here?
Judging from the fact that changing MAX_AT_ONCE fixes the problem and that jdt.apt.pluggable.tests.ScalingTests.testGeneratingLotsOfFiles() passes (ie, simple scenarios with large numbers of files are unaffected), I am guessing that the problem has something to do with the way that additional compilation units are added to the list in jdt.internal.core.builder.AbstractImageBuilder.compile(). That is, I'm guessing this has something to do with types that are referenced within the code and discovered during compilation.
Personal opinion: I believe the code that maintains the list of items to compile is would benefit from being refactored either to use java.util.ArrayList, or if that is not acceptable for some reason, then a jdt.internal version of the same thing. The logic of maintaining the data structure and the logic of using the data structure are interwoven in a way that makes it hard to figure out exactly what's going on, and that has been a source of ongoing bugs over the years.

The JDT/Core team is under-resourced and currently focused on Java 8 work. I doubt if I can get to fix any time soon.
If Bin or anyone can come up with a patch, I will be happy to do a review.

I actually don't know that code very well - Olivier Thomann worked on that part of the JDT/APT integration. It is in the Java compiler, where it decides what compilation units to pass to the compilation listeners. I recall it being extremely confusing code, with a collection of units to compile that is being modified by several different routines on the call stack.
To my eye - with apologies to the people who actually wrote it, under constraints that I'm sure I'm not aware of - it is code that would benefit from being refactored so that the data structure (i.e., the collection) is not intermingled with the compilation logic.
I think the basic issue here has to do with the fact that when the number of classes to be compiled exceeds a certain number, JDT breaks them down into batches; APT is just nested within compilation, so it ends up getting batched as well, inadvertently.

we too have been bitten by this bug. i took a bit of time to figure out what is going on and here is what i found:
suppose we set AbstractImageBuilder#MAX_AT_ONCE to 5 and have a project with the following classes:
T1{}, T2{}, T3{}, T4{}, T5{}, T6 extends T1{}.
the important bit above is to get a class that would depend on another that would in turn be compiled in a future bucket. so in order to reproduce the bug the first bucket would have to contain [T6,T5,T4,T3,T2] (this is how the bucket is built by my 3.8 install).
compilation of the bucket begins and when T6 is compiled the compiler compiles T1 since it is a dependency of T6. as a result a few things happen to T1's compilation unit:
* it is marked with AST.IsImplicitUnit * it is marked as compiled - and so will not be part of any future compilation bucket
after the bucket is compiled (it now contains [T6,T5,T4,T3,T2,*T1*]), Compiler.processAnnotations() is invoked and here when processing annotations a list of currentUnits[] is built from the bucket (Compiler#unitsToProcess) and any unit with ASTNode.isImplicitUnit is specifically filtered out. this is what is causing the bug: T1 will not be processed for annotations.
perhaps the thinking was that these implicit units will be passed through annotation processing when they are compiled in a future bucket, but as we can see they never will be because when building future buckets already compiled units are not included.
ASTNode.isImplicitUnit and its use in filtering units out of annotation processing was introduced in this commit:
commit 7fdea980e7fdbdb111b31c578044aa6d30cbcdb1 Author: Olivier Thomann <oliviert> Date: Sat Dec 16 20:35:30 2006 +0000
HEAD - Fix for 160773
unfortunately this is a rather big and general commit and does not leave many clues as to why the filtering was added.
i will leave it to someone more knowledgeable about this code to figure out if it should be removed or worked around. that said, a fix would be much appreciated. we are left with the following choices:
* use a patched jdt.core and distribute it across all installs in our team * switch from 3.8 to 4.3 when it ships and suffer until than * split our 2400 class project into modules which would be labor intensive
none of these options are attractive or simple :(

I don't see a good reason to exclude the implicit units from annotation processing. Doing that prevents the annotation processors to properly process all units referenced inside other units located at the beginning of the compilation process. All units end up being compiled but the annotation processors are only run for the direct referenced units which look bogus. I believe the check was there to make sure we don't run the annotation processors twice for some units.
So I would provide a fix that removes that check for implicit units and ask people involved in this thread to check if this is fixing their problem.
